{"title_page": "Bragan\u00e7a District", "text_new": "{{short description|District of Portugal}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Bragan\u00e7a\n| native_name             = \n| other_name              = \n| settlement_type         = [[Districts of Portugal|District]]\n<!-- images, nickname, motto -->\n| image_skyline           = Bragan\u00e7a49.jpg\n| image_caption           = Civil Governor's residence in the district seat of Bragan\u00e7a\n| image_flag              =\n| image_shield            = Bras\u00e3o_de_Bragan\u00e7a.png\n| motto                   = \n| nickname                = \n| etymology               = \n<!-- location -->\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = [[Portugal]]\n| subdivision_type1       = Region\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Norte Region, Portugal|Norte]]\n| subdivision_type2       = Subregion\n| subdivision_name2       = Alto Tr\u00e1s-os-Montes\n| subdivision_type3       = Historical Province\n| subdivision_name3       = Tr\u00e1s-os-Montes e Alto Douro\n| subdivision_type4       = District\n| subdivision_name4       = Bragan\u00e7a\n| parts_type              = Municipalities\n| parts_style             = para\n| p1                      = [[Alf\u00e2ndega da F\u00e9 Municipality|Alf\u00e2ndega da F\u00e9]]\n| p2                      = [[Bragan\u00e7a Municipality|Bragan\u00e7a]]\n| p3                      = [[Carrazeda de Ansi\u00e3es Municipality|Carrazeda de Ansi\u00e3es]]\n| p4                      = [[Freixo de Espada \u00e0 Cinta Municipality|Freixo de Espada \u00e0 Cinta]]\n| p5                      = [[Macedo de Cavaleiros Municipality|Macedo de Cavaleiros]]\n| p6                      = [[Miranda do Douro Municipality|Miranda do Douro]]\n| p7                      = [[Mirandela Municipality|Mirandela]]\n| p8                      = [[Mogadouro Municipality|Mogadouro]]\n| p9                      = [[Torre de Moncorvo|Moncorvo]]\n| p10                     = [[Vila Flor]]\n| p11                     = [[Vimioso Municipality|Vimioso]]\n| p12                     = [[Vinhais Municipality|Vinhais]]\n<!-- maps and coordinates -->\n| image_map               = LocalDistritoBraganca.svg\n| map_caption             = The location of the District of Bragan\u00e7a within continental Portugal\n| pushpin_map             = \n| pushpin_relief          = \n| pushpin_map_caption     =  \n| coordinates             = \n| coordinates_footnotes   = \n<!-- government type, leaders -->\n| leader_title1           = Civil Governor\n| leader_name1            = Jorge Manuel Nogueiro Gomes\n<!-- established -->\n| established_title       = Settlement\n| established_date        = \n<!-- area -->\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| area_total_sq_mi        = \n| area_land_sq_mi         = \n| area_water_sq_mi        = \n<!-- elevation -->\n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| elevation_ft            = \n<!-- population -->\n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = 136,252\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_density_sq_mi=\n| population_demonym      = \n<!-- time zone(s) -->\n| timezone1               = [[West European Time|WET]]\n| utc_offset1             = 0\n| timezone1_DST           = [[Western European Summer Time|WEST]]\n| utc_offset1_DST         = +1\n<!-- postal codes, area code -->\n| postal_code_type        = \n| postal_code             = \n| area_code_type          =  \n| area_code               = (+351) 273 XXX XXX\n| geocode                 = \n| iso_code                = \n| blank_name              = [[country code top-level domain|ccTLD]]\n| blank_info              = [[.pt]]\n| blank1_name             = Currency\n| blank1_info             = [[Euro]] (\u20ac)\n<!-- website, footnotes -->\n| website                 = \n| footnotes               = Statistics from [[Instituto Nacional de Estat\u00edstica|INE]] (2001); geographic detail from Instituto Geogr\u00e1fico Portugu\u00eas (2010)\n}}\n'''Bragan\u00e7a District''' ({{lang-pt|Distrito de Bragan\u00e7a}} {{IPA-pt|b\u027e\u0250\u02c8\u0263\u0250\u0303s\u0250||Pt-pt Bragan\u00e7a FF.ogg}}; {{lang-mwl|\u00c7trito de Berg\u00e1ncia}}) is a traditional political division of [[Portugal]], in the northeast corner bordering on [[Spain]] ([[Castile and Leon]] and [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]]) , covering 7.4% of the nation's continental landmass. The capital of the district, [[Bragan\u00e7a, Portugal|Bragan\u00e7a]], is {{convert|217|km}} from [[Porto]], the second largest town in Portugal, {{convert|107|km}} from the Spanish town of [[Zamora, Spain|Zamora]] and {{convert|169|km}} from   [[Salamanca]], also in Spain.<ref name=\"Quantitative\">Sreko Devjak et al. (2007), p.2</ref><ref>Abrunhosa (2002)</ref> Bragan\u00e7a is administratively divided in twelve municipalities and 299 parishes located in the north-eastern part of [[Tr\u00e1s-os-Montes (region)|Tr\u00e1s-os-Montes]].<ref name=Quantitative/> {{As of|2011|alt=As of the 2011 census}}, the total resident population was approximately 136,252. It is bordered by [[Spain]] ([[Castile and Leon]] and [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]]) in the north and northeast, [[Vila Real District]] in the west, [[Viseu District]] in the southwest and [[Guarda District]] in the south.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Domus Municipalis 4.jpg|thumb|235px|left|The ancient ''[[Domus Municipalis]]'' in the Roman [[civitas]] of ''Brigantia'' was the base of organized settlement]]\n[[File:Afonso first Duke of Braganza.jpg|left|235px|left|thumb|[[Afonso, Duke of Braganza|Afonso]], first [[Duke of Braganza]], whose Dukedom developed from the Bragan\u00e7\u00e3o family lands established in [[Castro de Avel\u00e3s]]]]\nDuring the Roman era, the territory was part of the much larger province of [[Gallaecia]], dependent administratively on [[Astorga, Spain|Astorga]] and the gold, iron and silver trade route. Although names similar to Bragan\u00e7a appeared around 666 B.C. (Wamba) or 569 A.D. (Council of Lugo), a territory identifiable as ''Bragan\u00e7a'' only appeared after the [[Celt]]s who baptised one of their main settlements ''Brigantia'', in the second century, which was later Latinized to ''Bragan\u00e7a''. But this settlement was limited.\n\nThe region's name was derived from the traditional feudal history of the northern region: the Bragan\u00e7\u00e3os family of [[Castro de Avel\u00e3s]] were the basis of this lineage that included Fern\u00e3o Mendes, who later married the Infanta Sancha (daughter of [[Afonso Henriques]]), inheriting the region on the death of the King. The Bragan\u00e7\u00e3os would maintain their hold on the region until 1258, when [[Afonso III of Portugal|Afonso III]] transferred the title to Nuno Martins, but the name ''Bragan\u00e7\u00e3o'' would continue to influence the region. Eventually, the King [[Afonso V of Portugal|Afonso V]] established the [[Duchy|Dukedom]] of the ''[[Duchy of Braganza]]'' for his uncle, [[Afonso, Duke of Braganza|Afonso, Count of Barcelos]] to strengthen the ties of the crown to the land. When the royal [[House of Braganza]] ascended to the throne of Portugal (through [[John IV of Portugal|John IV]]), the significance of ''Bragan\u00e7a'', as the hereditary seat of the Kings and Emperors of Portugal was sealed.\n\nThe district of Bragan\u00e7a was constituted upon the creation of the district system on 25 April 1835; a creation of the Liberal government, it was inspired by the [[France|French]] ''[[d\u00e9partements]]'', with the objective to ''\"facilitate the action of government...and permit access to the authorities\"''.<ref>Lu\u00eds Silveira (1997)</ref> The establishment of the districts was primarily done to counteract the centralizing tendencies of the governmental authority.<ref>Governador Civil de Braga (2002), p.1</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n\n===Physical geography===\nThe district is composed of two distinct regions described in terms of its geographic differences: the northern areas, with the higher altitudes constitute the ''Terra Fria Transmontana'' (''Cold lands''), and the [[Alto Tr\u00e1s-os-Montes]], where the landscape is dominated gentler slopes of the plateau; and the southern areas, the ''Terra Quente Trasmontana'' (''Hot Lands''), where the climate is milder, marked by the valleys of the [[Douro River]] and its tributaries. Its area allows a wide diversity of landscapes, and the district is known for its climatic differences (nine months of winter and three of heat), its rugged geomorphology, an aging population and urban to rural migration of its residents over time.\n\nIt is the [[Douro River]] that characterizes the geography, dividing the borders within the district, its southern frontier and extreme northeast borders with Spain. It is in the Douro valley that the lowlands of the district are primarily located, although almost all are 400 metres above sea level, with the exception of the municipality of [[Mirandela Municipality|Mirandela]] and its rivers. In addition to the Douro, the rivers of the district run north to south (or northeast to southwest) within the Douro watershed. The principal rivers are the Tua River, which springs from the mountains of Mirandela, at the confluence of Tuela and Raba\u00e7al Rivers, and the Sabor River, which springs in Spain, and crosses the eastern part of the district. Both rivers have a network of tributaries, such as the Baceiro River (feeding the Tuela), the Mente River (serving the Raba\u00e7al), and the Azibo River (supporting the Sabor).\n\nThe mountain ranges divide these water courses: the Serra da Nogueira (approximately 1320 metres) separates the Tuela and Sabor valleys; more to the south, the Serra de Bornes (1199 metres), in the municipalities of [[Macedo de Cavaleiros Municipality|Macedo de Cavaleiros]] and [[Alf\u00e2ndega da F\u00e9 Municipality|Alf\u00e2ndega da F\u00e9]] separate the Tua and Sabor Rivers; to the east, the columns of the Serra do Mogadouro (997 metres) separate the Sabor and Douro; and in the north, at the border with Spain, the largest mountains in the region the Serra da Coroa (1274 metres), north of [[Vinhais Municipality|Vinhais]], and the Serra de Montesinho (1400 metres) at the frontier, shield the Spanish autonomous communities from Portugal. A major part of the dams in the district are located along the Douro; the Valeira, Pocinho, Saucelle, Aldead\u00e1vila, Bemposta, Picote and Miranda Dams, along the main river, and the Azibo, Nuzedo de Baixo and Rebordelo, along its tributaries.\n\n====Ecoregions/protected areas====\nBragan\u00e7a includes several natural sanctuaries, such as the ''[[Montesinho Natural Park|Parque Natural de Montesinho]]'', the ''[[Parque Natural do Douro Internacional]]'', and the ''Paisagem Protegida da Albufeira do Azibo'', oasises in the northwest part of the [[Iberian peninsula|peninsula]].\n\n===Human geography===\nConsisting of twelve municipalities, the district of Bragan\u00e7a is the fifth largest district of Portugal: \n* [[Alf\u00e2ndega da F\u00e9 Municipality|Alf\u00e2ndega da F\u00e9]]\n* [[Bragan\u00e7a Municipality|Bragan\u00e7a]]\n* [[Carrazeda de Ansi\u00e3es Municipality|Carrazeda de Ansi\u00e3es]]\n* [[Freixo de Espada \u00e0 Cinta Municipality|Freixo de Espada \u00e0 Cinta]]\n* [[Macedo de Cavaleiros Municipality|Macedo de Cavaleiros]]\n* [[Miranda do Douro Municipality|Miranda do Douro]]\n* [[Mirandela Municipality|Mirandela]]\n* [[Mogadouro Municipality|Mogadouro]]\n* [[Torre de Moncorvo|Moncorvo]]\n* [[Vila Flor]]\n* [[Vimioso Municipality|Vimioso]]\n* [[Vinhais Municipality|Vinhais]]\n\n==Politics==\nOne of 18 Portuguese districts, this administrative division serves to define electoral units for proportional representation in national elections; administrative centres for police, courts and other public orders; and some local offices of ministries.<ref name=\"Game\">James P. Kahan et al. (1999), p.1</ref> Although Bragan\u00e7a has a Civil Governor, nominated by the Ministry of Home Affairs ({{lang-pt|Ministro da Administra\u00e7\u00e3o Interna}}), his/her role is limited to issues of public security, and local governance.<ref name=Game/>\n\n===Summary of votes and seats won 1976-2019===\n{{electiontable|Summary of election results from Bragan\u00e7a district, 1976-2019}}'''Summary of election results from the district of Bragan\u00e7a (1976\u20132019)'''\n|- class=\"unsortable\"\n!rowspan=2|Parties!!%!!S!!%!!S!!%!!S!!%!!S!!%!!S!!%!!S!!%!!S!!%!!S!!%!!S!!%!!S!!%!!S!!%!!S!!%!!S!!%!!S!!%!!S\n|- class=\"unsortable\" align=\"center\"\n!colspan=2 | 1976\n!colspan=2 | 1979\n!colspan=2 | 1980\n!colspan=2 | 1983\n!colspan=2 | 1985\n!colspan=2 | 1987\n!colspan=2 | 1991\n!colspan=2 | 1995\n!colspan=2 | 1999\n!colspan=2 | 2002\n!colspan=2 | 2005\n!colspan=2 | 2009\n!colspan=2 | 2011\n!colspan=2 | 2015\n!colspan=2 | 2019\n|-\n| align=\"left\"| [[Socialist Party (Portugal)|PS]] || 22.6 || 1 || 22.2 || 1 || 21.3 || 1 || 30.4 || 1 || 22.7 || 1 || 19.2 || 1 || 25.7 || 1 || 40.3 || 2  || 39.7 || 2 || 30.0 || 1 || style=\"background:#FF66FF;\"|'''42.1''' || style=\"background:#FF66FF;\"|'''2''' || 33.0 || 1 || 26.1 || 1 || 34.1 || 1 || 36.5 || 1\n|-\n| align=\"left\"| [[Social Democratic Party (Portugal)|PSD]] || style=\"background:#FF9900;\"|'''33.3''' || style=\"background:#FF9900;\"|'''2''' || align=center colspan=4 rowspan=2|''In [[Democratic Alliance (Portugal)|AD]]'' || style=\"background:#FF9900;\"|'''35.8''' || style=\"background:#FF9900;\"|'''2''' || style=\"background:#FF9900;\"|'''39.2''' || style=\"background:#FF9900;\"|'''2''' || style=\"background:#FF9900;\"|'''60.8''' || style=\"background:#FF9900;\"|'''3''' || style=\"background:#FF9900;\"|'''57.9''' || style=\"background:#FF9900;\"|'''3''' || style=\"background:#FF9900;\"|'''44.8'''|| style=\"background:#FF9900;\"|'''2''' || style=\"background:#FF9900;\"|'''45.1''' || style=\"background:#FF9900;\"|'''2''' || style=\"background:#FF9900;\"|'''53.2''' || style